      styles/
        global.css
        components.css
    package.json
    tsconfig.json
    astro.config.mjs
    README.md
    LICENSE
    
    
## Development Guidelines
- Follow best practices for code organization, readability, and maintainability.
- Use consistent naming conventions and coding styles across the project.
- Write clear and concise comments where necessary to explain complex logic or design decisions.
- Ensure that the website is fully responsive and works well on all devices and screen sizes.
- Implement accessibility best practices to ensure the site is usable by all users, including those with disabilities.
- Optimize images and other assets to improve load times and performance.
- Regularly test the website across different browsers and devices to ensure compatibility and a consistent user experience.
- Use version control (e.g., Git) to manage changes.

## Integrations
- GitHub: For showcasing projects and linking to repositories.
- Social media platforms (e.g., LinkedIn, Twitter): For linking to social profiles in the contact section.
- Blogging platforms: For linking to writings and articles in the writings section.
- Analytics tools (e.g., Google Analytics): For tracking website performance and user interactions.
- SEO tools (e.g., Google Search Console): For monitoring and improving search engine visibility.
- Performance monitoring tools (e.g., Lighthouse): For assessing and optimizing website performance.

## SEO Best Practices
- Use descriptive and keyword-rich titles and meta descriptions for each page.
- Implement structured data (e.g., JSON-LD) to enhance search engine understanding of the content.
- Ensure that all images have descriptive alt text for accessibility and SEO.
- Use semantic HTML elements (e.g., <header>, <main>, <footer>) to improve the structure and accessibility of the content.
- Create a sitemap.xml file to help search engines crawl the site effectively.
- Use clean and descriptive URLs for each page.
- Optimize page load times by minimizing CSS and JavaScript, and leveraging browser caching.
- Regularly update the content to keep it fresh and relevant for search engines and users.

## Accessibility Best Practices
- Ensure that all interactive elements (e.g., buttons, links) are keyboard accessible.
- Use ARIA attributes where necessary to enhance the accessibility of custom components.
- Provide sufficient color contrast between text and background for readability.
- Use semantic HTML to improve the structure and accessibility of the content.
- Ensure that all images have descriptive alt text for screen readers.
- Implement skip navigation links to allow users to bypass repetitive content.
- Test the website with screen readers and other assistive technologies to ensure a good user experience for all users.
- Provide captions and transcripts for any multimedia content (e.g., videos, audio).

## Execution Rules
- Provide changes before execution and ask for confirmation before proceeding with any code changes.
- Ask for two options after each change: "Keep changes" or "Revert changes".
- If "Keep changes" is selected, implement the changes in relevant files.
- If "Revert changes" is selected, discard the changes and maintain the current state of the codebase.

## Response Format
- Add a brief English comment to every code line.
- When modifying a file, provide the COMPLETE file (partial snippets FORBIDDEN).
- After each step, suggest the logical "Next step".
- If a design decision is needed, present options and wait for approval.
- Keep explanations concise and structured.
- Always ensure that the code adheres to the defined architecture and rules.
- When adding new dependencies, justify their necessity and ensure they do not violate the "no heavy dependencies" rule.
- When asked to "create" or "scaffold" files, provide ONLY
  shell commands (mkdir/touch). Do NOT generate file contents
  unless explicitly asked with "write the code for [filename]".
- When asked to "refactor" or "modify" files, provide the COMPLETE modified file with comments. Do NOT provide diffs or partial snippets.
- Always maintain the integrity of the project structure and naming conventions.
- When asked to "explain" a piece of code, provide a concise summary of its purpose and how it fits into the overall architecture. Avoid lengthy explanations or tangential information.
- ALWAYS write code directly to the file, never to the chat. Use the file editing tool to create or modify files. Only use the chat for explanations, questions, or options.
